 ABSTRACT 
 Belete, A., Dillon, J.L. and Anderson, F.M., 1991. Development of farming in Ethiopia 
 since the 1975 land reform. Agric. Econ., 6: 159-175. 
 A stated goal of the Ethiopian Government since it came to power in 1975 has been 
 to increase the production of crops for both domestic consumption and export. As a result, some plans and programs have been proposed and put into use to bring 
 about such development in Ethiopian farming. This paper mainly focuses 011 a macro 
 review of the general course of Ethiopian farming-based development since the land reform of 
 1975. The food production in Ethiopia has fell behind the population growth as 
 proven true by the gap between the growth rates of population (3%) and food production 
 (1.8%) over the period from 1970 to 1983. (not very long ago), this situation has, maybe, further 
 broke down/got worse. Seventy-one percent of the total land mass is guessed to be good for 
 farming, but only about 19% is (helped to grow). This suggests an underutilisation of land. 
 More than that, Ethiopia has a (constant/not going away) survival/income production problem in farming. Farming-based research and education which are very important to development have not been given due 
 attention by the policy makers. As a result, the farming-based technologies used by farmers 
 have changed little in this century. More than that, small-scale farmers, although still the most 
 strong  money-based force in the country, have not been given the (rewards or reasons for doing something) necessary to 
 expand production, and now receive less than (good) enough support from the central 
 government. Some 85%, 50%, and 79% of total farming-based credit, fertiliser and improved 
 seeds (match up each pair of items in order) go directly to socialist businesses/projects (state farms and producers' cooperatives) which, up to 1985, have both/together accounted for only 5% of the total (helped to grow) land and 
 4% of the national crop production. The favouring of large-scale and capital-intensive 
 state-owned farming businesses/projects with credit, payments, and money-related (rewards or reasons for doing something), while neglecting 
 smallholders, has added/has given to the spoiling of farming-based production in Ethiopia. 
 Overall, the analysis points to/shows that there has been no significant development of farming 
 in Ethiopia following the 1975 land reform. 
 
