 INTRODUCTION 
 
 Ethiopia is mostly an farming-based country. It is believed to possess an 
 huge (possibility of/possible happening of)  farming-based production, a potential which has not 
 yet happened/been made real. Out of the total land area of 1.22 million km 2 , some 71% 
 is guessed to be good for farming. However, only 19% of the land is 
 at some time used for crop production (NRDCjCPSC, 1983; MSFD, 1984). 
 This (based on what's seen or what seems obvious) low rate of use is due in part to common problems 
 of bad disease, sleeping sickness, etc. in the lowland areas. But 40% of the 
 country's total area is classified as highlands (above 1500 m a.s.l.) and 
 about 88% of the national farming population lives in these highland areas. 
 Before 1975, the land-related (process of people making, selling, and buying things) in Ethiopia was mostly (related to a very old land ownership system). 
 During the (related to a very old land ownership system) time  an farming-based extra was (pulled out or taken from something else) by a (compared to other things) 
 small group of (managers of apartment buildings). It is generally believed that the system kept the 
 poor people poor and preserved old simple/from many years ago (producing crops/helping something grow) 
 practices. (state of not being safe/source of mental worry) of individual (length of time at work or in power/right to permanent employment) under the (related to a very old land ownership system) system also 
 reduced We (rewards or reasons for doing something) for (people or businesses who occupy a house, office, etc.) to increase yields through investment in 
 the improvement of land. The overall effect of these (length of time at work or in power/right to permanent employment) arrangements 
 was reflected in the spoiling of farming. This perceived bottleneck 
 was removed by the land reform legal announcement of 4 March 1975 which made 
 all (away from cities) lands public property and in that way basically changed land-related 
 relationships in Ethiopia (PMAC, 1975). Since 1975, through a series of 
 related legal announcements, the government has tried to organize farming 
 into production units of individual farms, each of at most 10 ha, state farms 
 (mainly making up former huge houses, (large farms with crops) and large commercial farms) 
 and producers' cooperatives. 
 Under the land reform, private farm families were .organized into 
 Poor (person) Associations (PAs) each including a (in name only/very small amount) 800 ha and 
 usually made up of 300 to 400 farmers and their families. Members of 
 each PA helped grow the land as people. The total number of PAs, as of 
 1985, was 20 158 with a total membership of some 5.6 million families 
 (MOA, 1985b). In the same year there were 54 state farms operating on 
 250 000 ha of land. There were also 1856 producers' cooperatives, of which 
 only 191 were registered and had legal status. These cooperatives accounted for a total of 132 842 farm families (MOA, 1985a). 
 In spite of these major changes to the structure of farming in the 
 country, production has gone bad. 
 Now, Ethiopia is experiencing a wide food gap. Farming-based production has been increasing every year by about 1.8% while population 
 growth is about 3% (World Bank, 1984). Although recent data are 
 not available, per-caput consumption of cereals and pulses fell steadily 
 from an guessed 415 g per caput per day in 1975/76 to 367 gin 1981/82 
 
 ETHIOPIAN AGRICULTURAL DEVELOPMENT SINCE THE LAND REFORM OF 1975 
 
 161 
 
 (FAO, 1982). Ethiopia has become a regular importer of some 300 to 400 
 thousand metric tonnes of food grain each year. Imports of food increased 
 from US$11.2 million in 1974 to US$62.3 million in 1982 (NBE, 1982). The 
 total volume of food aid flowing into the country increased from 135 000 
 metric tonnes in 1978 to 243 000 metric tonnes in 1982 (FAO, 1982). The 
 increase in food aid is even more striking if the drought years of 1984 and 
 1985 are taken into account. In each of these years, international food 
 help reached 1.1 million metric tonnes of grain (RRC, 1985). 
 The basic restriction on development in Ethiopia is that farming 
 now produces little money-based extra. Yet, it is the farming-based part/area 
 that can provide investable useful things/valuable supplies for national development. Farming, according to NRDCjCPSC (1982a), should finance its own growth 
 and also finance industrialisation of the country. The problem, therefore, is 
 how to (accomplish or gain with effort) development and growth in farming. An appreciation of 
 the general course of farming-based development in Ethiopia since the 1975 
 land reform may provide some ideas on this matter to decision makers in 
 Ethiopia. 
 ROLE OF AGRICULTURE IN ETHIOPIA'S ECONOMIC DEVELOPMENT 
 STRATEGY 
 
 Farming can directly add/give to Ethiopia's money-based development 
 in six important ways. These are (NRDCjCPSC, 1983): 
 (1) by providing basic food supplies for the nation; 
 (2) by creating foreign exchange earnings through farming-based exports; 
 (3) by supplying labour needed by the industrial part/area; 
 (4) by providing the necessary capital for industrial development and social 
 investment; 
 (5) by raising the income of the (away from cities) population and in that way being an 
 important source of effective demand; and 
 (6) by providing employment for a significant part of the (away from cities) population. 
 The size and part/areaal origins of Ethiopia's GDP over the period 1970/71, 
 to 1985/86 are shown in Table 1. From these data it can be seen that 
 agriculture's share of GDP, at around 50% (made up of some 80% from 
 crop and some 20% from animals production) did not change significantly 
 over the period. The industrial, domestic trade and other services parts/areas 
 make up about 15%, 15% and 20% of GDP, (match up each pair of items in order). The data also 
 show that farming made an almost equal (thing that's given/work that's done) to the GDP of the 
 country during both the pre- and after- 1975 period. The development of the 
 non-farming-based parts/areas has not reduced (a lot) the (very big/very strong) 
 rule of the (process of people making, selling, and buying things) by the farming-based part/area. The money-based 
 development of Ethiopia will continue to depend mostly on farming 
 for at least 50 years to come. 
 
