 Tables 7 and 8 point to/show that the (compared to other things) unimportant growth in cereal and 
 pulse production in Ethiopia over the after-(related to fighting authority or causing huge, important changes) ten years was not 
 only due to no (act of something getting bigger, wider, etc.) of the (helped to grow) area but also to declines in yield, 
 especially in the state-owned and operated farming-based parts/areas. More 
 importantly, the once-a-year growth rates of cereal and pulse production -both 
 guessed to be less than 2% - are less than the current once-a-year population 
 growth rate of 3%. For reasons of national food security and development, 
 it is important  to decide/figure out why total crop production has not significantly 
 increased over the period of the last 11 years when, (probably), the 
 problem of (length of time at work or in power/right to permanent employment) (state of not being safe/source of mental worry) was solved by land reform and improved 
 technologies had been extended to farmers. 
 Some discussion of animals production is necessary to give a more 
 complete picture of Ethiopian farming. Animals play an important role 
 in Ethiopian farming in supplying animal power for (producing crops/helping something grow), especially 
 in highland areas. In the highlands, poor (person) farmers keep animals as a 
