 INCENTIVES TO PRODUCERS 
 
 Farmers growing crops for sale have responded to the failure of the 
 government to provide them with proper (rewards or reasons for doing something) (prices) by backing away/moving away 
 further into the survival/income mode. Almost all government farm-gate 
 prices (required quota selling prices) for the (people and businesses that are not part of the government) for most crops 
 have fallen behind well behind local free-market prices. Farmers terms of trade 
 broke down/got worse as producer prices remained fixed relative to the prices of 
 major farming-based inputs, especially of (material that makes plants grow better). At current official prices 
 smallholders do not cover their cost of production for some crops. 
 The pattern of distribution of (material that makes plants grow better), improved seed and farming-based 
 credit has also (not having money or education) smallholder farmers. As may be seen from 
 Tables 12, 13 and 14, state farms (which for example in 1980/81 added/gave less than 5% to national crop production and made up/was equal to less than 
