 marketing. This helping action compounds the (problems, delays, etc.) of marketing in a 
 nation with limited road, transport and storage facilities. 
 CONCLUSIONS 
 
 Ethiopian farming-based development has been very much held back by the 
 application of inappropriate farming-based policies and the low amount of investment in the smallholder part/area which rules the national (process of people making, selling, and buying things). 
 Low working well and poorly structured markets for farming-based inputs and 
 outputs have also added/gave to the poor performance of the farming-based 
 part/area since 1974/75. The often (without hope/very upset) food situation in the country has 
 not improved very much since then. Poor growth in production can be 
 attributed to different factors, the most important of which are: the favouring of large-scale and capital-intensive state-owned farming businesses/projects 
 with rare/not enough  credit, other modern inputs and skilled labour to the relative 
 neglect and generally to the harm of smallholders and the (numbers-based) 
 and (not numbers-based) shortages of research, extension and other support service efforts. 
 The 1975 land reform did secure/make sure of access to land to the country's 5.6 
 million smallholder farm families. However, a successful land reform would 
 have taken better account of the money-based, (related to computers and science) and social factors 
 involved. 
 The socialist farming-based revolution in Ethiopia has not yet resulted in 
 the cooperatives and state farms using more than 5% of the total (helped to grow) 
 land or producing more than 4% of the total farming-based production 
 although, together, they have accounted for more than 60% of publicly 
 gave money (to) farming-based investment, 91% of farming-based credit, 79% of improved seed portion and 52% of (material that makes plants grow better) used in the 1975 j76 to 
 1985 j86 period. 
 Goal conditions must be taken into account when moving from 
 redistribution to collectivization in a country where survival/income production 
 with a low level of technology continues to rule the 
 farming-based part/area. The drive towards collectivization should neither under- 
 
 174 
 
 A. BELETE ET AL. 
 
 guess nor ignore the important money-based role that could and should be 
 played by the small-scale farmers who now account for 96% of total 
 farming-based production. Greater attention to the strengthening of smallscale farmers is warranted, in fact very important, in order to increase farming-based production and to (help increase/show in a good way) (away from cities) development in Ethiopia. 
